    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1964-11-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1964-11-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="311"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d311">
                <head>311. Memorandum for the Files<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d311fn1"
                        >Source: Library of Congress, Manuscript Division, <persName
                            corresp="#p_HWA_1">Harriman</persName> Papers, Box 448, Congo (3).
                        Confidential. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_HWA_1"
                        >Harriman</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1964-11-05">November 5, 1964</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>It is becoming increasingly clear that our incautious broadcasting of our concern
                    about the fate of the Americans in Stanleyville has increased the rebel
                    appreciation of the value of the hostages, thereby increasing the danger to
                    them. The country team’s judgment in these matters and that of our Embassy in
                    Belgium have so far been consistently sound, and it is clear that we should have
                    paid more attention to their views. I have on several occasions registered this
                    opinion, including <pb facs="0485" n="452" xml:id="pg_452"/> my objection to the
                    stand-down of the aircraft in the Congo for seven days.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>W.A.H.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
